# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: discriminant-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA is closely related to analysis of variance (ANOVA) and regression analysis, which also attempt to express one dependent variable as a linear combination of other features or measurements.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] However, ANOVA uses categorical independent variables and a continuous dependent variable, whereas discriminant analysis has continuous independent variables and a categorical dependent variable (*i.e.* the class label).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Logistic regression and probit regression are more similar to LDA than ANOVA is, as they also explain a categorical variable by the values of continuous independent variables.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These other methods are preferable in applications where it is not reasonable to assume that the independent variables have a normal distribution, which is a fundamental assumption of the LDA method.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA is also closely related to principal component analysis (PCA) and factor analysis in that they both look for linear combinations of variables which best explain the data.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA explicitly attempts to model the difference between the classes of data.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] PCA, in contrast, does not take into account any difference in class, and factor analysis builds the feature combinations based on similarities rather than differences.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant analysis is also different from factor analysis in that it is not an interdependence technique: a distinction between independent variables and dependent variables (also called criterion variables) must be made.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA works when the measurements made on independent variables for each observation are continuous quantities.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] When dealing with categorical independent variables, the equivalent technique is discriminant correspondence analysis.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant analysis is used when groups are known a priori (unlike in cluster analysis).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Each case must have a score on one or more quantitative predictor measures, and a score on a group measure.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In simple terms, discriminant function analysis is classification - the act of distributing things into groups, classes or categories of the same type.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The original dichotomous discriminant analysis was developed by Sir Ronald Fisher in 1936.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It is different from an ANOVA or MANOVA, which is used to predict one (ANOVA) or multiple (MANOVA) continuous dependent variables by one or more independent categorical variables.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant function analysis is useful in determining whether a set of variables is effective in predicting category membership.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Consider a set of observations ${\vec {x}}$ (also called features, attributes, variables or measurements) for each sample of an object or event with known class y .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This set of samples is called the training set in a supervised learning context.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The classification problem is then to find a good predictor for the class y of any sample of the same distribution (not necessarily from the training set) given only an observation ${\vec {x}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Without any further assumptions, the resulting classifier is referred to as quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA instead makes the additional simplifying homoscedasticity assumption (*i.e.* that the class covariances are identical, so $\Sigma _{0}=\Sigma _{1}=\Sigma$ ) and that the covariances have full rank.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This means that the criterion of an input ${\vec {x}}$ being in a class y is purely a function of this linear combination of the known observations.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It is often useful to see this conclusion in geometrical terms: the criterion of an input ${\vec {x}}$ being in a class y is purely a function of projection of multidimensional-space point ${\vec {x}}$ onto vector ${\vec {w}}$ (thus, we only consider its direction).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In other words, the observation belongs to y if corresponding ${\vec {x}}$ is located on a certain side of a hyperplane perpendicular to ${\vec {w}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The location of the plane is defined by the threshold c .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The assumptions of discriminant analysis are the same as those for MANOVA.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The analysis is quite sensitive to outliers and the size of the smallest group must be larger than the number of predictor variables.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It has been suggested that discriminant analysis is relatively robust to slight violations of these assumptions, and it has also been shown that discriminant analysis may still be reliable when using dichotomous variables (where multivariate normality is often violated).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant analysis works by creating one or more linear combinations of predictors, creating a new latent variable for each function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These functions are called discriminant functions.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The number of functions possible is either $N_{g}-1$ where $N_{g}$ = number of groups, or p (the number of predictors), whichever is smaller.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The first function created maximizes the differences between groups on that function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The second function maximizes differences on that function, but also must not be correlated with the previous function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This continues with subsequent functions with the requirement that the new function not be correlated with any of the previous functions.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Given group j , with $\mathbb {R} _{j}$ sets of sample space, there is a discriminant rule such that if $x\in \mathbb {R} _{j}$ , then $x\in j$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant analysis then, finds “good” regions of $\mathbb {R} _{j}$ to minimize classification error, therefore leading to a high percent correct classified in the classification table.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Each function is given a discriminant score to determine how well it predicts group placement.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] An eigenvalue in discriminant analysis is the characteristic root of each function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It is an indication of how well that function differentiates the groups, where the larger the eigenvalue, the better the function differentiates.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This however, should be interpreted with caution, as eigenvalues have no upper limit.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The eigenvalue can be viewed as a ratio of *SS*between and *SS*within as in ANOVA when the dependent variable is the discriminant function, and the groups are the levels of the IV.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This means that the largest eigenvalue is associated with the first function, the second largest with the second, etc..
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Some suggest the use of eigenvalues as effect size measures, however, this is generally not supported.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Instead, the canonical correlation is the preferred measure of effect size.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It is similar to the eigenvalue, but is the square root of the ratio of *SS*between and *SS*total.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It is the correlation between groups and the function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Another popular measure of effect size is the percent of variance for each function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This is calculated by: $\left({\frac {\lambda _{x}}{\sum _{i}\lambda _{i}}}\right)\times 100$ where $\lambda _{x}$ is the eigenvalue for the function and $\sum _{i}\lambda _{i}$ is the sum of all eigenvalues.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This tells us how strong the prediction is for that particular function compared to the others.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Percent correctly classified can also be analyzed as an effect size.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The kappa value can describe this while correcting for chance agreement.Kappa normalizes across all categorizes rather than biased by a significantly good or poorly performing classes.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Canonical discriminant analysis (CDA) finds axes (*k* − 1 canonical coordinates, *k* being the number of classes) that best separate the categories.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These linear functions are uncorrelated and define, in effect, an optimal *k* − 1 space through the *n*-dimensional cloud of data that best separates (the projections in that space of) the *k* groups.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Because LDA uses canonical variates, it was initially often referred as the "method of canonical variates" or canonical variates analysis (CVA).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The terms *Fisher's linear discriminant* and *LDA* are often used interchangeably, although Fisher's original article actually describes a slightly different discriminant, which does not make some of the assumptions of LDA such as normally distributed classes or equal class covariances.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This measure is, in some sense, a measure of the signal-to-noise ratio for the class labelling.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] When the assumptions of LDA are satisfied, the above equation is equivalent to LDA.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Be sure to note that the vector ${\vec {w}}$ is the normal to the discriminant hyperplane.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] As an example, in a two dimensional problem, the line that best divides the two groups is perpendicular to ${\vec {w}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Generally, the data points to be discriminated are projected onto ${\vec {w}}$ ; then the threshold that best separates the data is chosen from analysis of the one-dimensional distribution.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] There is no general rule for the threshold.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] However, if projections of points from both classes exhibit approximately the same distributions, a good choice would be the hyperplane between projections of the two means, ${\vec {w}}\cdot {\vec {\mu }}_{0}$ and ${\vec {w}}\cdot {\vec {\mu }}_{1}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In the case where there are more than two classes, the analysis used in the derivation of the Fisher discriminant can be extended to find a subspace which appears to contain all of the class variability.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Suppose that each of C classes has a mean $\mu _{i}$ and the same covariance $\Sigma$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] where $\mu$ is the mean of the class means.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This means that when ${\vec {w}}$ is an eigenvector of $\Sigma ^{-1}\Sigma _{b}$ the separation will be equal to the corresponding eigenvalue.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] If $\Sigma ^{-1}\Sigma _{b}$ is diagonalizable, the variability between features will be contained in the subspace spanned by the eigenvectors corresponding to the *C* − 1 largest eigenvalues (since $\Sigma _{b}$ is of rank *C* − 1 at most).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These eigenvectors are primarily used in feature reduction, as in PCA.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The eigenvectors corresponding to the smaller eigenvalues will tend to be very sensitive to the exact choice of training data, and it is often necessary to use regularisation as described in the next section.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] If classification is required, instead of dimension reduction, there are a number of alternative techniques available.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] For instance, the classes may be partitioned, and a standard Fisher discriminant or LDA used to classify each partition.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] A common example of this is "one against the rest" where the points from one class are put in one group, and everything else in the other, and then LDA applied.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This will result in C classifiers, whose results are combined.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Another common method is pairwise classification, where a new classifier is created for each pair of classes (giving *C*(*C* − 1)/2 classifiers in total), with the individual classifiers combined to produce a final classification.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The typical implementation of the LDA technique requires that all the samples are available in advance.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] However, there are situations where the entire data set is not available and the input data are observed as a stream.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In this case, it is desirable for the LDA feature extraction to have the ability to update the computed LDA features by observing the new samples without running the algorithm on the whole data set.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] For example, in many real-time applications such as mobile robotics or on-line face recognition, it is important to update the extracted LDA features as soon as new observations are available.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] An LDA feature extraction technique that can update the LDA features by simply observing new samples is an *incremental LDA algorithm*, and this idea has been extensively studied over the last two decades.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Chatterjee and Roychowdhury proposed an incremental self-organized LDA algorithm for updating the LDA features.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In other work, Demir and Ozmehmet proposed online local learning algorithms for updating LDA features incrementally using error-correcting and the Hebbian learning rules.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Later, Aliyari et al. derived fast incremental algorithms to update the LDA features by observing the new samples.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In practice, the class means and covariances are not known.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] They can, however, be estimated from the training set.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Either the maximum likelihood estimate or the maximum a posteriori estimate may be used in place of the exact value in the above equations.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Although the estimates of the covariance may be considered optimal in some sense, this does not mean that the resulting discriminant obtained by substituting these values is optimal in any sense, even if the assumption of normally distributed classes is correct.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Another complication in applying LDA and Fisher's discriminant to real data occurs when the number of measurements of each sample (i.e., the dimensionality of each data vector) exceeds the number of samples in each class.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In this case, the covariance estimates do not have full rank, and so cannot be inverted.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] There are a number of ways to deal with this.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] One is to use a pseudo inverse instead of the usual matrix inverse in the above formulae.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] However, better numeric stability may be achieved by first projecting the problem onto the subspace spanned by $\Sigma _{b}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] where I is the identity matrix, and $\lambda$ is the *shrinkage intensity* or *regularisation parameter*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This leads to the framework of regularized discriminant analysis or shrinkage discriminant analysis.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Also, in many practical cases linear discriminants are not suitable.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA and Fisher's discriminant can be extended for use in non-linear classification via the kernel trick.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Here, the original observations are effectively mapped into a higher dimensional non-linear space.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Linear classification in this non-linear space is then equivalent to non-linear classification in the original space.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The most commonly used example of this is the kernel Fisher discriminant.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] LDA can be generalized to multiple discriminant analysis, where *c* becomes a categorical variable with *N* possible states, instead of only two.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Analogously, if the class-conditional densities $p({\vec {x}}\mid c=i)$ are normal with shared covariances, the sufficient statistic for $P(c\mid {\vec {x}})$ are the values of *N* projections, which are the subspace spanned by the *N* means, affine projected by the inverse covariance matrix.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These projections can be found by solving a generalized eigenvalue problem, where the numerator is the covariance matrix formed by treating the means as the samples, and the denominator is the shared covariance matrix.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In addition to the examples given below, LDA is applied in positioning and product management.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In bankruptcy prediction based on accounting ratios and other financial variables, linear discriminant analysis was the first statistical method applied to systematically explain which firms entered bankruptcy vs. survived.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Despite limitations including known nonconformance of accounting ratios to the normal distribution assumptions of LDA, Edward Altman's 1968 model is still a leading model in practical applications.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In computerised face recognition, each face is represented by a large number of pixel values.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Linear discriminant analysis is primarily used here to reduce the number of features to a more manageable number before classification.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Each of the new dimensions is a linear combination of pixel values, which form a template.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The linear combinations obtained using Fisher's linear discriminant are called *Fisher faces*, while those obtained using the related principal component analysis are called *eigenfaces*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In marketing, discriminant analysis was once often used to determine the factors which distinguish different types of customers and/or products on the basis of surveys or other forms of collected data.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Logistic regression or other methods are now more commonly used.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Estimate the Discriminant Function Coefficients and determine the statistical significance and validity—Choose the appropriate discriminant analysis method.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The direct method involves estimating the discriminant function so that all the predictors are assessed simultaneously.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The stepwise method enters the predictors sequentially.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The two-group method should be used when the dependent variable has two categories or states.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The multiple discriminant method is used when the dependent variable has three or more categorical states.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Use Wilks's Lambda to test for significance in SPSS or F stat in SAS.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The most common method used to test validity is to split the sample into an estimation or analysis sample, and a validation or holdout sample.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The estimation sample is used in constructing the discriminant function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The validation sample is used to construct a classification matrix which contains the number of correctly classified and incorrectly classified cases.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The percentage of correctly classified cases is called the *hit ratio*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Plot the results on a two dimensional map, define the dimensions, and interpret the results.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The statistical program (or a related module) will map the results.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The map will plot each product (usually in two-dimensional space).
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The distance of products to each other indicate either how different they are.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The dimensions must be labelled by the researcher.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This requires subjective judgement and is often very challenging.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] The main application of discriminant analysis in medicine is the assessment of severity state of a patient and prognosis of disease outcome.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] For example, during retrospective analysis, patients are divided into groups according to severity of disease – mild, moderate, and severe form.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Then results of clinical and laboratory analyses are studied to reveal statistically different variables in these groups.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Using these variables, discriminant functions are built to classify disease severity in future patients.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Additionally, Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) can help select more discriminative samples for data augmentation, improving classification performance.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] In biology, similar principles are used in order to classify and define groups of different biological objects, for example, to define phage types of Salmonella enteritidis based on Fourier transform infrared spectra, to detect animal source of *Escherichia coli* studying its virulence factors etc.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] This method can be used to separate the alteration zones.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] For example, when different data from various zones are available, discriminant analysis can find the pattern within the data and classify it effectively.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Discriminant function analysis is very similar to logistic regression, and both can be used to answer the same research questions.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Logistic regression does not have as many assumptions and restrictions as discriminant analysis.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] However, when discriminant analysis’ assumptions are met, it is more powerful than logistic regression.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Unlike logistic regression, discriminant analysis can be used with small sample sizes.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] It has been shown that when sample sizes are equal, and homogeneity of variance/covariance holds, discriminant analysis is more accurate.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Despite all these advantages, logistic regression has none-the-less become the common choice, since the assumptions of discriminant analysis are rarely met.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Geometric anomalies in higher dimensions lead to the well-known curse of dimensionality.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Nevertheless, proper utilization of concentration of measure phenomena can make computation easier.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] An important case of these *blessing of dimensionality* phenomena was highlighted by Donoho and Tanner: if a sample is essentially high-dimensional then each point can be separated from the rest of the sample by linear inequality, with high probability, even for exponentially large samples.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] These linear inequalities can be selected in the standard (Fisher's) form of the linear discriminant for a rich family of probability distribution.
[src:discriminant-analysis/discriminant-function-analysis] Data separability by classical linear discriminants simplifies the problem of error correction for artificial intelligence systems in high dimension.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] In statistics, **kernel Fisher discriminant analysis (KFD)**, also known as **generalized discriminant analysis** and **kernel discriminant analysis**, is a kernelized version of linear discriminant analysis (LDA).
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] Intuitively, the idea of LDA is to find a projection where class separation is maximized.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] where $l_{i}$ is the number of examples of class $\mathbf {C} _{i}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] The goal of linear discriminant analysis is to give a large separation of the class means while also keeping the in-class variance small.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] This, in turn, is equivalent to maximizing $I(\mathbf {w} ,\lambda )=\mathbf {w} ^{\text{T}}\mathbf {S} _{B}\mathbf {w} -\lambda (\mathbf {w} ^{\text{T}}\mathbf {S} _{W}\mathbf {w} -1)$ , where $\lambda$ is the Lagrange multiplier.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] At the maximum, the derivatives of $I(\mathbf {w} ,\lambda )$ with respect to $\mathbf {w}$ and $\lambda$ must be zero.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] Further, note that $\mathbf {w} \in F$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] Explicitly computing the mappings $\phi (\mathbf {x} _{i})$ and then performing LDA can be computationally expensive, and in many cases intractable.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] For example, F may be infinite dimensional.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] The extension to cases where there are more than two classes is relatively straightforward.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] where the $\mathbf {w} _{i}$ are the columns of $\mathbf {W}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] where $\mathbf {m} ^{\phi }$ is the mean of all the data in the new feature space.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] $\mathbf {A} ^{*}$ can then be computed by finding the $(c-1)$ leading eigenvectors of $\mathbf {N} ^{-1}\mathbf {M}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] where ${\bar {\mathbf {y} }}_{j}$ is the projected mean for class j and $D(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is a distance function.
[src:discriminant-analysis/kernel-fisher-discriminant-analysis] Kernel discriminant analysis has been used in a variety of applications.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] In machine learning, a **linear classifier** makes a classification decision for each object based on a linear combination of its features.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] A simpler definition is to say that a linear classifier is one whose decision boundaries are *linear*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Such classifiers work well for practical problems such as document classification, and more generally for problems with many variables (features), reaching accuracy levels comparable to non-linear classifiers while taking less time to train and use.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] where ${\vec {w}}$ is a real vector of weights and *f* is a function that converts the dot product of the two vectors into the desired output.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] (In other words, ${\vec {w}}$ is a one-form or linear functional mapping ${\vec {x}}$ onto **R**.) The weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ is learned from a set of labeled training samples.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] The superscript T indicates the transpose and $\theta$ is a scalar threshold.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] A more complex *f* might give the probability that an item belongs to a certain class.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] For a two-class classification problem, one can visualize the operation of a linear classifier as splitting a high-dimensional input space with a hyperplane: all points on one side of the hyperplane are classified as "yes", while the others are classified as "no".
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] A linear classifier is often used in situations where the speed of classification is an issue, since it is often the fastest classifier, especially when ${\vec {x}}$ is sparse.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Also, linear classifiers often work very well when the number of dimensions in ${\vec {x}}$ is large, as in document classification, where each element in ${\vec {x}}$ is typically the number of occurrences of a word in a document (see document-term matrix).
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] In such cases, the classifier should be well-regularized.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] There are two broad classes of methods for determining the parameters of a linear classifier ${\vec {w}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] They can be generative and discriminative models.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Methods of the former model joint probability distribution, whereas methods of the latter model conditional density functions $P({\rm {class}}|{\vec {x}})$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] The second set of methods includes discriminative models, which attempt to maximize the quality of the output on a training set.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Additional terms in the training cost function can easily perform regularization of the final model.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Discriminative training often yields higher accuracy than modeling the conditional density functions.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] However, handling missing data is often easier with conditional density models.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] All of the linear classifier algorithms listed above can be converted into non-linear algorithms operating on a different input space $\varphi ({\vec {x}})$ , using the kernel trick.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Discriminative training of linear classifiers usually proceeds in a supervised way, by means of an optimization algorithm that is given a training set with desired outputs and a loss function that measures the discrepancy between the classifier's outputs and the desired outputs.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Popular loss functions include the hinge loss (for linear SVMs) and the log loss (for linear logistic regression).
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] If the regularization function R is convex, then the above is a convex problem.
[src:discriminant-analysis/linear-classifier] Many algorithms exist for solving such problems; popular ones for linear classification include (stochastic) gradient descent, L-BFGS, coordinate descent and Newton methods.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In machine learning and statistical classification, **multiclass classification** or **multinomial classification** is the problem of classifying instances into one of three or more classes (classifying instances into one of two classes is called binary classification).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Multiclass classification should not be confused with multi-label classification, where multiple labels are to be predicted for each instance (e.g., predicting that an image contains both an apple and an orange, in the previous example).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] From the confusion matrix of a multiclass model, we can determine whether a model does better than chance.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] It is assumed that the confusion matrix $(n_{i,j})_{i,j}$ contains at least one non-zero entry in each row, that is $\lambda _{i}>0$ for any i .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Finally we call "normalized confusion matrix" the matrix of conditional probabilities $(\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=i))_{i,j}=\left({\frac {n_{i,j}}{n_{i.}}}\right)_{i,j}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We have $\mathrm {Lift} (A,B)>1$ if and only if events A and B occur simultaneously with a greater probability than if they were independent.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In other words, if one of the two events occurs, the probability of observing the other event increases.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] A first condition to satisfy is to have $\mathrm {Lift} (y=i,{\hat {y}}=i)\geq 1$ for any i .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] And the quality of a model (better or worse than chance) does not change if we over- or undersample the dataset, that is if we multiply each row $R_{i}$ of the confusion matrix by a constant $c_{i}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Thus the second condition is that the necessary and sufficient conditions for doing better than chance need only depend on the normalized confusion matrix.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The condition on lifts can be reformulated with One versus Rest binary models : for any i , we define the binary target variable $y_{i}$ which is the indicator of event $\{y=i\}$ , and the binary model ${\hat {y}}_{i}$ of $y_{i}$ which is the indicator of event $\{{\hat {y}}=i\}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Each of the ${\hat {y}}_{i}$ models is a "One versus Rest" model. $\mathrm {Lift} (y=i,{\hat {y}}=i)$ only depends on the events $\{y=i\}$ and $\{{\hat {y}}=i\}$ , so merging or not merging the other classes doesn't change its value.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We therefore have $\mathrm {Lift} (y=i,{\hat {y}}=i)=\mathrm {Lift} (y_{i}=1,{\hat {y}}_{i}=1)$ and the first condition is that all binary One versus Rest models are better than chance.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Dividing by $n_{1.}n_{2.}$ we find that the necessary and sufficient condition on the normalized confusion matrix is $\mathrm {sensitivity} \ \mathrm {specificity} -(1-\mathrm {sensitivity} )(1-\mathrm {specificity} )\geq 0\iff \mathrm {sensitivity} +\mathrm {specificity} -1\geq 0\iff J\geq 0$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This brings us back to the classical binary condition: Youden's J must be positive (or zero for random models).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] A random model is a model that is independent of the target variable.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This property is easily reformulated with the confusion matrix.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] All the columns of the confusion matrix are then proportional to the non-zero vector $(n_{i.})_{i}$ , which implies that the confusion matrix is of rank 1.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Conversely, if this matrix is of rank 1, the non-zero columns of the matrix are proportional to each other, and therefore proportional to their sum $(n_{i.})_{i}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] So there exists a family of numbers $(\beta _{j})_{j}$ such that $n_{i,j}=n_{i.}\beta _{j}$ for any i and j .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Summing this equations over i gives $n_{.j}=\beta _{j}n$ , hence $n_{i,j}n=n_{i.}n_{.j}$ for any i and j .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This proposition shows that the model ${\hat {y}}$ of y is uninformative if and only if there are two families of numbers $(\alpha _{i})_{i}$ and $(\beta _{j})_{j}$ such that $\mathbb {P} (\{y=i\}\cap \{{\hat {y}}=j\})=\alpha _{i}\beta _{j}$ for any i and j .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We define generalized likelihood ratios calculated from the normalized confusion matrix: for any i and $j\not =i$ , let $\mathrm {LR} _{i,j}={\frac {\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=j)}{\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=i)}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] By dividing by $\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=j)$ and subtracting 1, we deduce the second formulation.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We saw above that a better-than-chance model (or a random model) must verify $\mathrm {Lift} (y=i,{\hat {y}}=i)\geq 1$ for any i and $\lambda _{i}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] According to the previous corollary, likelihood ratios are thus greater than or equal to 1.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Conversely, if the likelihood ratios are greater than or equal to 1, the theorem shows that we have $\mathrm {Lift} (y=i,{\hat {y}}=i)\geq 1$ for any i and $\lambda _{i}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] If all the entries of the confusion matrix are non-zero, this means that all the likelihood ratios are greater than or equal to 1, and at least one of these inegalities is strict.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] A model that satisfies the first condition but not the second is random, since we then have $\mathbb {P} (\{{\hat {y}}=j\}\cap \{y=i\})=\mathbb {P} (y=i)\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=i)=\mathbb {P} (y=i)\mathbb {P} ({\hat {y}}=j\mid y=j)=\alpha _{i}\beta _{j}$ for any i and j .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We can rewrite the first condition in a more familiar way, noting x the observed value of ${\hat {y}}$ , $\theta$ the value to be estimated of y and ${\hat {\theta }}(x)$ the set $argmax_{\theta }\mathbb {P} (x\mid \theta )$ : for any x we have $x\in {\hat {\theta }}(x)$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] We deduce that *a model is better-than-random or random if and only if it is a maximum likelihood estimator of the target variable*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The performance of a better-than-chance model can be estimated using multiclass versions of metrics such as balanced accuracy or Youden's J .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] If $\mathrm {balanced\ accuracy} =1$ , in other words $J=1$ , the model is perfect.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] And for any random model, we have $\mathrm {balanced\ accuracy} ={\frac {1}{K}}$ (if, for example, we draw a uniform random number from the K labels, we have exactly one chance in K of predicting the correct value of the target variable).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] On a balanced data set ( $\lambda _{i}={\frac {1}{K}}$ for any i ), balanced accuracy is equal to the rate of well-classified observations.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] On any data set, if a model does better than chance, we have $J\geq 0$ and $\mathrm {balanced\ accuracy} \geq {\frac {1}{K}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] But the converse is not true when $K>2$ , as we can see from this example: the confusion matrix ${\begin{pmatrix}0&3&0\\1&2&0\\0&0&3\end{pmatrix}}$ is that of a bad model (=worse than chance) since $\mathrm {LR} _{2,1}=0$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] However, 5 of the 9 observations are correctly classified.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This also shows that poor model performance on one of the modalities is not compensated for by good performance on the other modalities.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The set of normalized confusion matrices is called the ROC space, a subspace of ${\mathopen {[}}0,1{\mathclose {]}}^{m^{2}}$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] If E denotes the subset of the ROC space made up of random models or models that do better than chance, one can show that the topological boundary of E is the set of elements of E for which at least one of the likelihood ratios is equal to 1.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] And random models are those models whose likelihood ratios are all equal to 1.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] When $K=2$ , the boundary between models that do better than chance and bad models is equal to the set of random models (see article on the roc curve for more details), but it is strictly larger as soon as $K>2$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] And if $K=3$ , we can calculate the volume occupied by bad models in the ROC space: they occupy 90% of this space, whereas it's only 50% when $K=2$ .
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This section discusses strategies for reducing the problem of multiclass classification to multiple binary classification problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] It can be categorized into *one vs rest* and *one vs one*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The techniques developed based on reducing the multi-class problem into multiple binary problems can also be called problem transformation techniques.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] One-vs.-rest (OvR or *one-vs.-all*, OvA or *one-against-all*, OAA) strategy involves training a single classifier per class, with the samples of that class as positive samples and all other samples as negatives.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This strategy requires the base classifiers to produce a real-valued score for its decision (see also scoring rule), rather than just a class label; discrete class labels alone can lead to ambiguities, where multiple classes are predicted for a single sample.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Although this strategy is popular, it is a heuristic that suffers from several problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Firstly, the scale of the confidence values may differ between the binary classifiers.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Second, even if the class distribution is balanced in the training set, the binary classification learners see unbalanced distributions because typically the set of negatives they see is much larger than the set of positives.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] However, empirical studies have shown one-vs-rest can perform competitively with more sophisticated multiclass methods.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In the *one-vs.-one* (OvO) reduction, one trains *K* (*K* − 1) / 2 binary classifiers for a K-way multiclass problem; each receives the samples of a pair of classes from the original training set, and must learn to distinguish these two classes.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] At prediction time, a voting scheme is applied: all *K* (*K* − 1) / 2 classifiers are applied to an unseen sample and the class that got the highest number of "+1" predictions gets predicted by the combined classifier.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Like OvR, OvO suffers from ambiguities in that some regions of its input space may receive the same number of votes.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This section discusses strategies of extending the existing binary classifiers to solve multi-class classification problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Several algorithms have been developed based on neural networks, decision trees, k-nearest neighbors, naive Bayes, support vector machines and extreme learning machines to address multi-class classification problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] These types of techniques can also be called algorithm adaptation techniques.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Multiclass perceptrons provide a natural extension to the multi-class problem.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Instead of just having one neuron in the output layer, with binary output, one could have N binary neurons leading to multi-class classification.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In practice, the last layer of a neural network is usually a softmax function layer, which is the algebraic simplification of N logistic classifiers, normalized per class by the sum of the N-1 other logistic classifiers.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Neural Network-based classification has brought significant improvements and scopes for thinking from different perspectives.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Extreme learning machines (ELM) is a special case of single hidden layer feed-forward neural networks (SLFNs) wherein the input weights and the hidden node biases can be chosen at random.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Many variants and developments are made to the ELM for multiclass classification.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] k-nearest neighbors kNN is considered among the oldest non-parametric classification algorithms.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] To classify an unknown example, the distance from that example to every other training example is measured.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The k smallest distances are identified, and the most represented class by these k nearest neighbours is considered the output class label.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Naive Bayes is a successful classifier based upon the principle of maximum a posteriori (MAP).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] This approach is naturally extensible to the case of having more than two classes, and was shown to perform well in spite of the underlying simplifying assumption of conditional independence.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Decision tree learning is a powerful classification technique.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The tree tries to infer a split of the training data based on the values of the available features to produce a good generalization.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The algorithm can naturally handle binary or multiclass classification problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The leaf nodes can refer to any of the K classes concerned.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Support vector machines are based upon the idea of maximizing the margin i.e. maximizing the minimum distance from the separating hyperplane to the nearest example.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The basic SVM supports only binary classification, but extensions have been proposed to handle the multiclass classification case as well.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In these extensions, additional parameters and constraints are added to the optimization problem to handle the separation of the different classes.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Multi expression programming (MEP) is an evolutionary algorithm for generating computer programs (that can be used for classification tasks too).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] MEP has a unique feature: it encodes multiple programs into a single chromosome.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Each of these programs can be used to generate the output for a class, thus making MEP naturally suitable for solving multi-class classification problems.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Hierarchical classification tackles the multi-class classification problem by dividing the output space into a tree.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Each parent node is divided into multiple child nodes and the process is continued until each child node represents only one class.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Several methods have been proposed based on hierarchical classification.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Based on learning paradigms, the existing multi-class classification techniques can be classified into batch learning and online learning.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Batch learning algorithms require all the data samples to be available beforehand.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] It trains the model using the entire training data and then predicts the test sample using the found relationship.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The online learning algorithms, on the other hand, incrementally build their models in sequential iterations.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] In iteration t, an online algorithm receives a sample, xt and predicts its label ŷt using the current model; the algorithm then receives yt, the true label of xt and updates its model based on the sample-label pair: (xt, yt).
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Recently, a new learning paradigm called progressive learning technique has been developed.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The progressive learning technique is capable of not only learning from new samples but also capable of learning new classes of data and yet retain the knowledge learnt thus far.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] The performance of a multi-class classification system is often assessed by comparing the predictions of the system against reference labels with an evaluation metric.
[src:discriminant-analysis/multiclass-classification] Common evaluation metrics are Accuracy or macro F1.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] In statistics, a **quadratic classifier** is a statistical classifier that uses a quadratic decision surface to separate measurements of two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] It is a more general version of the linear classifier.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] Statistical classification considers a set of vectors of observations **x** of an object or event, each of which has a known type *y*.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] This set is referred to as the training set.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] The problem is then to determine, for a given new observation vector, what the best class should be.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] In the special case where each observation consists of two measurements, this means that the surfaces separating the classes will be conic sections (i.e., either a line, a circle or ellipse, a parabola or a hyperbola).
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] In this sense, we can state that a quadratic model is a generalization of the linear model, and its use is justified by the desire to extend the classifier's ability to represent more complex separating surfaces.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] Quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) is closely related to linear discriminant analysis (LDA), where it is assumed that the measurements from each class are normally distributed.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] Unlike LDA however, in QDA there is no assumption that the covariance of each of the classes is identical.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] When the normality assumption is true, the best possible test for the hypothesis that a given measurement is from a given class is the likelihood ratio test.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] Suppose there are only two groups, with means $\mu _{0},\mu _{1}$ and covariance matrices $\Sigma _{0},\Sigma _{1}$ corresponding to $y=0$ and $y=1$ respectively.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] After some rearrangement, it can be shown that the resulting separating surface between the classes is a quadratic.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] The sample estimates of the mean vector and variance-covariance matrices will substitute the population quantities in this formula.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] While QDA is the most commonly used method for obtaining a classifier, other methods are also possible.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] One such method is to create a longer measurement vector from the old one by adding all pairwise products of individual measurements.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] Finding a quadratic classifier for the original measurements would then become the same as finding a linear classifier based on the expanded measurement vector.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] For linear classifiers based only on dot products, these expanded measurements do not have to be actually computed, since the dot product in the higher-dimensional space is simply related to that in the original space.
[src:discriminant-analysis/quadratic-classifier] This is an example of the so-called kernel trick, which can be applied to linear discriminant analysis as well as the support vector machine.
